I too have an AR for home protection.  I have handguns and shotguns but it's the
AR that's my 'go to' gun.  Don't let anyone give you any grief about it.  Up
close, it's got excellent stopping power - certainly more than any handgun.
Nearly zero recoil and muzzle flash make it a good night fighter.

I'm not sure that I'd want a flashlight attached to the rifle but having one - a
good one, such as the SureFire - at hand is a good idea.

I have an Armson OEG (the forerunner of the Trijicon Reflex sights) for my AR
but I'm also left eyed and don't have any problems using it.  At this time, the
radioactive element is dead and I'm waiting for them to get new one's in - I
don't feel at all disadvantaged with the iron sights.  Unless you have a huge
budget for toys and the resolve to actually learn to use the reflex type sights,
I suspect that iron sights will serve you well enough.  Trijicon is awfully
proud of their products and the price reflects that - however, I wouldn't use
anything that hasn't been proven in combat.  Essentially, I tend to go with the
&quot;keep it simple&quot; line.  Fewer things to go bad at the wrong time.

And, before the shotgun guys and the handgun guys come calling with their advice
as why their stuff is better than my AR - I live in the woods, have neither kids
nor neighbors to worry about and I happen to like and, more importantly, trust
my AR.
Cheers,
jc

