Perhaps with FMJ ammo but even then likely not.  At close ranges the small .22
cal bullets are at the most unstable point in their flight and tend to break up
and not penetrate so deeply.  I make sure of that by using soft point ammo.  Up
close the .223 is extremely deadly.  It's only beyond 100 yards or so that I
believe they become less effective and reliable on human targets.  Personally,
I consider the max range to be 150 yards and anything beyond nothing more than
wishful thinking.   (Please note that, having been through this many times in
the past, I must insist that everyone take the following into consideration:
this range conclusion is based on specific things:  my rifle, the ammo it's
loaded with and, most importantly, my experience with this combination.  Others
can base their own conclusions on whatever they like - I am not in the least
interested in any ballistic charts, alternate experience or whatever else
someone might  care to offer as to why they think I am wrong about my range
conclusions.  I am not proposing this as an absolute rule nor do I suggest that
anyone else go by these figures.  I'm just stating what I think are the
limitations on my rifle/ammo combination.  If you don't agree, that's fine.  I
don't care to hear about it).

Now, all that said, I do agree with the bayonet proposal and in fact, I have one
near by that I can stick on if I feel the need.  I have a huge muzzle flash
hider on my AR (it improved the accuracy substantially) and the bayonet only
sticks out about 6&quot; or so but what the hell, if nothing else it looks pretty bad
ass.  And I think in some situations, looking bad assed can be an advantage.
Cheers,
jc

